	   <a name=96815946522830></a>
	   <form action=http://www1.allakhazam.com/perl/strategy/mrate.pl name=f96815946522830><tr><td id=headerrow><span id=sj>Gosh, those armor buffs are expensive.  Are they worth it?</span></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=1032><span id= >Ebonygem</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>3 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Tue, Sep 5th 9:11 AM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[4.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>One of the line of buffs we get as clerics are armor buffs.&nbsp;&nbsp;These spells improve the armor of the beneficiary.  They do not absorb damage or do anything else but improve armor class.  Generally, an armor blessing has a significant casting cost.  So, when - if ever - is it good to use this line of buffs?<br><br>Unlike the center/daring/brave/valor/resolute line of buffs which should be kept cast all the time on every party member, the armor blessings should be cast at selected times on selected people.  An armor buff is a trade off of down time.  Is it worth the wait to recover mana for the extra defense?  (This isn't a trivial amount of time either.  A 19th level cleric in a full group casting Spirit Armor for 75 mana a cast will drain over 4 bubbles of his ~500 mana to armor up the whole group.  That is a long wait for the group - and it happens each time the blessing fades.)  <br><br>To begin with - let us consider how your defense works.  It appears that your defensive rating is compared to the MOBs attack rating - the differential between them puts you on a table of results ranging from miss to maximum damage.  A random number is generated and compared to the table to get the result of the attack.  The better your defense is vs the MOB's attack rating - the less you get hit and the less you get hit for larger amounts of damage.  While the armor value of these buffs may seem small compared to your total defense - in reality they add a level or two to your effective defense, potentially a big deal.  So knowing the costs of the spells and being able to make an estimate of their effectiveness - when should a cleric use them?<br><br>The time the armor line of spells shines brightest is when they are cast on the tank(s) who are constantly being hit.  If you are fighting a constant stream of low blues - the armor buffs on the people fighting are a great bargin.  You will save far more mana not healing because of the armor buff than the buff cost to cast.  It is well worth the down time up front since you are almost certain to get paid back several times over in mana savings.   Keep in mind that a pet can benefit from the armor spell as well - if it is getting the brunt of the attacks, then you should cast your armor blessing on the pet.<br><br>Another time the armor is quite valuable is when you plan to fight very dangerous monsters.  Here the goal isn't so much to save healing costs and it is to avoid deaths.  When you are hunting red monsters - much of your time is spent recovering from a few really tough fights.  The armor didn't have many hits to defend against - and the ones you did get were from a powerful critter who didn't have much trouble hitting you with or without the armor spell.  However, when you consider the sizable down time a death will cause and the time it will take to recover the lost experience - the time lost in casting the armor blessings makes sense.<br><br>The last time the armor spells are a clear win is when your other casters are still meditating and you are full mana.  Then the armor buffs are "free" and should be cast.  <br><br>If you are planning on exploring new areas where the MOBs could be dangerous - then the armor buffs may make sense.  In most cases you will not find them useful, but there will be a few times when you are happy you have them.  Think of the armor blessings as a form of insurance - on average they are time/mana lossers - but they help stave off disasters once in a while.<br><br>Casting armor spells on people who don't get hit often but have reasonablly good armor ratings is not generally cost effective either.  These would be people like secondary tanks and the clerics, folks who have nice armor but do not spend much time being attacked.  Keep a careful watch on who you heal - if the secondary tank (or cleric) is rarely being healed, then they aren't a good candidate for an armor buff.<br><br>Pure casters are a bad bet for your armor spells.  The reason why this is so is two fold.  First, casters have rotten defenses anyway.  The armor blessing doesn't bring up the defense enough to make the moster's attacks much weaker.  Second, the casters rarely get hit many times.  (Yes, they may need healing - even frequently - but the damage comes from only a few hits.)  Only when you are fighting the most dangerous of MOBs should you bother casting the armor line on the casters.  And even then - the armor spell is more for the mental outlook of the caster than any real defensive benifit.<br><br>So, to summerize:<br><br>Cast armor spells 1) on fighters who are being beaten upon by a constant stream of blues; 2) on pets who are the mainline tank for the group; 3) on everybody in really dangerous situtations, 4) on the main target(s) of MOB agresssion in most cases.<br><br>Perhaps cast armor spells 1) when you are exploring; 2) on secondary tanks; 3) on heavily armored healers.<br><br>Armor spells are not cost effective when given to pure casters, or anybody with very poor armor.  However, the armor spell can be a psychological boost to a caster - which might in itself be worthwhile.<br><br>Lastly, it can be hard to explain to the party why it is some people are getting armored and others not.  If someone makes it an issue - I recomend buffing them and trying to explain your strategy later.  Hopefully your careful explanation over the next half an hour or so will resolve the issue.  If not, &lt;sigh&gt; then go ahead and keep them all buffed and accept a few extra minutes of down time each hour. <br><br>Hope you find this helpful and informative.<br><br>May Innoruuk bless your efforts,<br><br><br><br>Ebonygem Val`Sharess - - RZ   <br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
